review_blob: 33 cl bottle, pours golden with a huge white head, aroma of elderflower,  yeast, malt and lactic acid, taste follows the nose, sticky mouthfeel, ok finish,  very ordinary.
33 cl bottle, pours dark with a light head, aroma of dark fruits, malt, brown sugar and yeast, fairly sweet, ok finish, good but not great overall.
75 cl bottle, pours dark with a light head, aroma of dark fruits, malt, yeast and alcohol, taste follows the nose, very sweet, ok overall but nothing special.
75 cl bottle, pours dark brown with a decent head, aroma of roasted malt, yeast and fruit, taste is similar to the nose, fairly long finish, good overall but reminds me more of a dubbel then tripel.
75 cl bottle, pours amber with a decent head, aroma of brett, fruit, malt and dough, taste follows the nose, long finish, somewhat similar to Orval, very nice overall.

37,5 cl bottle, pours dark golden with a nice big white head, aroma of fruit, grain and yeast, taste is fruit, malt and yeast, light drinkable with a smooth mouthfeel, alcohol well hidden, lovely overall beer.
33 cl bottle, pours dark golden with a nice big white head, aroma of fruit, grain and yeast, taste follows the nose, very light drinkable, lovely allround beer.

33 cl bottle, pours dark with a nice creamy head, aroma of chocolate, licorice, malt and coffee, taste follows the nose, very light drinkable at 10,2% but slightly watery on the palate, nice overall brew.

On tap, pours dark golden with a nice white head, aroma of yeast, spices, fruit and malt, taste follows the nose, alcohol is notiable, pretty sweet and heavy, decent but nothing special, reminds me of kasteel tripel.

beer_brewer_name: Brouwerij der Trappistenabdij De Achelse Kluis
review_blob: 75 cl bottle bb date 2014, pours dark brown with a minimal head, aroma of malt, dark fruit, yeast and cane sugar, taste follows the nose, very low carbonation, remiscent of rochefort, fairly smooth despite the low carbonation, enjoyable overall.
33 cl bottle, pours golden with a big white head, aroma of hops, fruit and malt, taste follows the nose, very plain tasting, pretty boring overall.
33 cl bottle, pours dark with a minor head, aroma of dark fruits, chocolate, licorice and some diacetyl, taste follows the nose, fairly sweet, bit watery palate, ok but fairly ordinary overall.

37,5 cl bottle, pours dark brown with a minor head, aroma is heavy whiskey with notes of malt and dried fruit as well, taste follows the nose, quite hot on the palate, obviously a sipper but most would be wise to share this with a friend.
beer_name: La Trappe Quadrupel Oak Aged Batch #8

review_blob: 37,5 cl bottle, pours dark brown with a minor head, aroma of malt caramel, brown sugar, oak, diacetyl, dark fruits and hint of booze, taste is similar to the aroma, fairly light drinkable but definitly a sipper, very enjoyable overall.
beer_name: La Trappe Quadrupel Oak Aged Batch #6

review_blob: 33 cl bottle, pours golden with a nice head, aroma of fruit, grain and yeast, taste follows the nose, light drinkable, bit watery palate, ok overall.

37,5 bottle that was bottled 9 months ago, pours golden with a minor head, aroma of brett, grape, lemon, malt and wood, taste is similar to the aroma, light drinkable and really not that sour at least not yet, still nice overall though.
33 cl bottle, pours dark golden with a nice white head, aroma of yeast, malt and fruit, taste follows the nose, bit fizzy mouthfeel, still light drinkable though.
33 cl bottle, pours golden with a nice white head, lots of lacings, aroma of yeast, grain and fruit, taste follows the nose, solid blond overall.

33 cl bottle, pours golden with a decent head, nice hoppy aroma of tropical fruit and malt, taste is pine, tropical fruit and malt, smooth mouthfeel, hard to believe this is only 4,4%, excellent session beer.

50 cl bottle, pours dark brown with a decent head, aroma of citrus, grapefruit and a floral note as well, taste is malty along with grapefruit and citrus, watery mouthfeel, very ordinary and downright boring overall.

33 cl bottle, pours golden with a big white head, lots of carbonation, aroma of yeast, fruit, malt, and grass, taste is yeasty, malty, grassy and with a note citrus as well, pretty dry but with some sweetness left, smooth mouthfeel, very nice overall.
75 cl bottle, pours pitch black with a dark head, aroma og coffee, malt, chocolate and yeast, taste follows the nose, smooth mouthfeel, nice overall, love the bottle decoration.
50 cl bottle, pours pitch black with a big dark head, aroma of roasted malt, coffee, chocolate, alcohol and wood, taste follows the nose, very sweet, decent but not great.

75 cl bottle, pours dark brown with very little carbonation, aroma of malt, cherry, acetone, vinegar and wood, taste follows the nose,fairly tart, very reminiscent of the Granc Cru, very good overall.
33 cl bottle, aroma of coffee, chocolate, licorice and caramel, taste follows the nose, smooth mouthfeel, suprisingly light drinkable, decent bitterness , very long finish, execellent overall!
beer_name: Fan Imperial X-mas Porter (Kunstner l No. 1)

review_blob: 50 cl bottle, pours dark brown, aroma of yeast, rye bread, malt, licorice and yeast, taste follows the nose, very long finish consisting of licorice, pretty good and interesting beer.
50 cl bottle, pours amber with a decent white head, aroma is malty, floral and fruity, taste is pine, malt, tropical fruit, decent bitterness,fairly long finish, smooth mouthfeel, very solid brew.
33 cl bottle, pours amber with a nice white head, aroma of tropical fruit, pine, malt and yeast, taste follows the nose, nice bitterness, smooth mouthfeel,  long finish, very good overall.
33 cl bottle, pours brownish with a decent creamy head, aroma of caramel malt, pine, fruit and alcohol, taste follows the nose, nice bitterness, sticky mouthfeel, ok but overall.
33 cl bottle, pours amber with a decent white head, aroma of fruit and pine, taste is malt, pine and fruit, nice lingering bitterness, alcohol well hidden, nice overall beer.
33 cl bottle, pouts golden with a nice white head, aroma of yeast, fruit and Dimethyl sulfide, taste basically follows the nose, weak finish.

33 cl bottle, pours brownish with a minor head, aroma of yeast, malt caramel, coffee and hops, taste follows the nose, surprisingly smooth mouthfeel, warming alcohol that is well integrated, very good overall.

75 cl bottle, pours amber with a nice big head, aroma of caramel, pine and tropical fruit, taste consists of burnt caramel and pine with a very noticeable presence of alcohol, too over the top for my liking.

33 cl bottle, pours dark golden with a nice big white head, some lacings and solid retention, aroma of fruit and yeast, taste consists of malt, fruit and yeast, semi weak finish, ok overall but far from anything special.

50 cl bottle, pours fairly clear golden with a decent white head, fair bit of lacings, aroma of grapefruit, grass, malt and slight peach, taste follows the nose, ok finish, a solid light drinkable session beer.
UPDATED: JAN 30, 2012

33 cl bottle, pours dark amber with a nice big head, aroma with notes of malt, floral hops, pine and fruit, taste is sweeter then expected with notes of caramel, pine and fruit, ok bitterness, decent finish, solid overall beer.
33 cl bottle, pours dark with a big creamy head, aroma of coffee, licorice and malt, taste follows the nose, fairly smooth, decent finish, solid beer overall.

33 cl bottle, pours reddish with a nice big head, plenty of lacings and solid retention, aroma of yeast, fruit, sugar and malt, taste follows the nose but with a sligt tartness, smooth mouthfeel, super beer.
UPDATED: JAN 30, 2012

37,5 cl bottle, pours dark with a minimal head, aroma of port, coffee and chocolate, taste is fairly sweet consisting of coffee, chocolate, ash and slight port, smooth yet powerful, nice long lingering finish, interesting and very good beer.
50 cl bottle, pours amber with a minor white head, aroma of malt, diacatyl and slight fruit, taste is malty caramel and slight fruit, abrupt finish, completly uninteresting.
50 cl bottle, pours a muddy dark golden, aroma of caramel, yeast and a slight floral note, taste follows the nose, sticky mouthfeel, not very hoppy at all, not my thing.

75 cl bottle vintage 2003, pours golden with a minor head, slight lacings, aroma of grapefruit, wood and brett, taste follows the nose, super smooth, decent finish, slightly sour and pretty light drinkable, overall very nice.

75 cl that was bottled in 2005, pours hazy golden/orange with a minimal head, aroma of wood, funk, lem and hay, taste is lemon, grape, funk and wood, fairly tart but slightly sweet as well, grapes are gone, bit sticky mouthfeel and not quite as smooth as cantillon usually are. Solid beer overall.
33 cl bottle, pours dark with a nice big head, aroma of cinnamom, ginger, cardemom and malt, taste folllows the nose, way over the top with the spices, certainly not my thing.
UPDATED: APR 17, 2012

37,5 cl bottle vintage 2005, pours reddish with a very minor head, aroma consists of brett, funk, lemon and wood, taste is similar to the aroma, slightly sour, super smooth and balanced, the grapes are pretty much gone at this point, but still a lovely beer.

37,5 cl bottle, pours reddish with a solid pink head, aroma of cherry, wood, yeast and malt, taste follows the nose, very vinous, ok sourness but no way extreme, slightly puckering mouthfeel but still easy to drink,, a nice brew overall.

75 cl bottle that says L12/06 and "expires" 2009, pours a light orange with a minor white head, aroma is pretty tart with notes of barnyard, wood, lemon and very subtle apricot, taste is pretty much the same and again the fruit is very subdued/subtle at this point, but thats perfectly natural, it is still very nice lambic overall no doubt.
